Part (c): Student Attendance Portal Using JSP and Servlet
Objective

To develop a simple Student Attendance Portal using JSP for collecting input and Servlet for handling data insertion into a MySQL database.

Concept Overview

This part demonstrates:

How JSP handles user interface (frontend)

How Servlet processes the form data (backend)

How JDBC is used to store the data into a database

The Model–View–Controller (MVC) structure — where JSP = View, Servlet = Controller, DB = Model

Database Setup (MySQL)

Run these SQL commands in MySQL before running the project:

CREATE DATABASE school;
USE school;

CREATE TABLE Attendance (
    StudentID INT,
    Date DATE,
    Status VARCHAR(10)
);


This creates a table to record each student's attendance date and status.

Project Structure
StudentAttendance/
│
├── attendance.jsp
├── WEB-INF/
│   └── web.xml
└── src/
    └── AttendanceServlet.java

JSP Page — attendance.jsp

This page serves as the frontend (View) where the user enters student details.

<%@ page language="java" contentType="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1" %>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Student Attendance Portal</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>Mark Student Attendance</h2>
    <form action="AttendanceServlet" method="post">
        Student ID: <input type="text" name="studentid" required><br><br>
        Date: <input type="date" name="date" required><br><br>
        Status: 
        <select name="status" required>
            <option value="Present">Present</option>
            <option value="Absent">Absent</option>
        </select><br><br>

        <input type="submit" value="Submit Attendance">
    </form>
</body>
</html>


Explanation:

The form collects Student ID, Date, and Status

Submits data to AttendanceServlet using POST

Servlet — AttendanceServlet.java

This servlet acts as the controller, taking form input, connecting to MySQL via JDBC, and inserting data.

import java.io.*;
import java.sql.*;
import javax.servlet.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;

public class AttendanceServlet extends HttpServlet {

    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            throws ServletException, IOException {

        response.setContentType("text/html");
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();

        // Step 1: Collect data from JSP form
        String id = request.getParameter("studentid");
        String date = request.getParameter("date");
        String status = request.getParameter("status");

        // Step 2: JDBC connection details
        String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/school";
        String user = "root"; // change as per your system
        String pass = "yourpassword"; // change as per your MySQL password

        try {
            // Step 3: Load JDBC driver
            Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

            // Step 4: Establish connection
            Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);

            // Step 5: Prepare SQL statement
            String sql = "INSERT INTO Attendance (StudentID, Date, Status) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";
            PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(sql);
            ps.setInt(1, Integer.parseInt(id));
            ps.setString(2, date);
            ps.setString(3, status);

            // Step 6: Execute insertion
            int result = ps.executeUpdate();

            // Step 7: Generate response
            if (result > 0) {
                out.println("<html><body>");
                out.println("<h2>Attendance recorded successfully!</h2>");
                out.println("<a href='attendance.jsp'>Mark Another Attendance</a>");
                out.println("</body></html>");
            } else {
                out.println("<h3>Failed to record attendance!</h3>");
            }

            // Step 8: Close connection
            con.close();

        } catch (Exception e) {
            out.println("<h3>Error: " + e.getMessage() + "</h3>");
        }
    }
}
